			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>Comparison of the expressiveness and performance of template-based code generation tools</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LechanceuxLuhunu.html">Lechanceux Luhunu</a>, <a href="../profile/EugeneSyriani.html">Eugene Syriani</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136021">10.1145/3136014.3136021</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagM">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It compares template-based code generation tools, i.e., generative compilation/code synthesis from models.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> A central evaluation dimension is performance of code generation approaches.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The paper empirically compares tools on expressiveness and performance across scenarios/benchmarks.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The subject of comparison is tooling infrastructure used in language/workbench-based generation workflows.
</li></ul></li></ul>
